<subSubSection id="4570392D805B790162A1E6FD7D0DC7B0" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" type="remarks">
<paragraph id="C6D7E4A730AC676736760A325306EFA1" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="CC84E26C872744A4F520749BEFF3239E" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName id="507263F6D1651C161824CB28EF1E4E16" authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F64BC28BB2773E67FF3E222ABA68320B" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="F4CCDA13779D4CA2562ECC0C76B136F7" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="954CA16D0E17767EF56040B1605DB715" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are distinguished from each other by their ontogeny (
<bibRefCitation id="D619BAE3365D64F0E83CC0CA159D42C9" author="Bandel, K" journalOrPublisher="Mitteilungen aus dem Geologisch-Palaeontologischen Institut der Universitaet Hamburg." pageId="19" pageNumber="30" pagination="65 - 164" refId="B5" refString="Bandel, K, 2001. The history of Theodoxus and Neritina connected with description and systematic evaluation of related Neritimorpha (Gastropoda). Mitteilungen aus dem Geologisch-Palaeontologischen Institut der Universitaet Hamburg. 85: 65 - 164" title="The history of Theodoxus and Neritina connected with description and systematic evaluation of related Neritimorpha (Gastropoda)." volume="85" year="2001">Bandel 2001</bibRefCitation>
). While the 
<taxonomicName id="4ED99915B6AAF7624512CCF81B18EADA" authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9BB64DA4061EBB89D739C4DBF91B2D8D" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species hatch from the spawn as miniature adult, 
<taxonomicName id="EE898F46700262124332F7D865F8BF82" genus="Nertina" lsidName="" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3AF20D67D25C816D10EF6F19B24953F9" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Nertina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species leave their spawn as planktotrophic larva that will float in the sea for a more or less extended period before its metamorphosis to a crawling young. However, at the adult stage the taxonomic separation of species of the genera 
<taxonomicName id="4869A091FA400961CAFA7234260390E1" authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="CAEE3300A3F47A972D22A2EE64B500AF" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="DEF7C9D4FA6A23B650942380EF6B1DFF" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="58D8A8A6E24FA9073F8861D0C164BB0A" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is not always easy. As most of the 
<taxonomicName id="5768E3D3FF32D0A91B7929D928F33A59" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="04B84493B7EE855FA3BB1E1FFBB8BFED" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. are marine species and usually have a denticulate border of the columella and two apophysis of the operculum, most species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="BE9F928EB495A294B3B4866A9F85B703" authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="F488CF19DC589BA01C8064B74A373B82" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are limnic and have a smooth border of the columella and one apophysis (the 
<normalizedToken id="36E066AEAF1C75498E89E756F05FC4FB" originalValue="“rib”">&quot;rib&quot;</normalizedToken>
); some also have a small apophysis, the peg, on the operculum (
<bibRefCitation id="85560874F5AB10B98D4A4D785528A505" author="Gloeer, P" journalOrPublisher="Die Tierwelt Deutschlands" pageId="19" pageNumber="30" refId="B22" refString="Gloeer, P, 2002. Die Suesswassergastropoden Nord- und Mitteleuropas. Bestimmungsschluessel, Lebensweise, Verbreitung. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands 73, 327 pp." title="Die Suesswassergastropoden Nord- und Mitteleuropas. Bestimmungsschluessel, Lebensweise, Verbreitung." volume="73" year="2002">
<normalizedToken id="A7F049E6DDFFE4F1E546CEE14D3E24A7" originalValue="Glöer">Gloeer</normalizedToken>
2002
</bibRefCitation>
). Further, in 
<taxonomicName id="43660354C2D3EDEF670E57BBD421E9A6" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Neritina" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="48B8F6CF7F9CD7626DF2FB4E60261C66" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Neritina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the peg is thick and strong, while in 
<taxonomicName id="725A690E7F644F11214D97C0DB695381" authorityName="Montfort" authorityYear="1810" class="Gastropoda" family="Neritidae" genus="Theodoxus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Archaeogastropoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="12" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="340616E2D349BDC94F4F5FE4394F8184" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="12">Theodoxus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
it is, if exists at all, small and weak. A revision of this family, particularly its subdivion in clearly defined genera is needed.
</paragraph>
